# VibeWarden Security Sidecar

This application runs behind VibeWarden, a security sidecar on port 8080.
The app itself listens on port {{ .UpstreamPort }}.
{{ if .AuthEnabled }}
## Authentication — DO NOT IMPLEMENT

Authentication is handled by VibeWarden (Ory Kratos). Do not write auth middleware,
session management, or login flows in application code.

Every request that reaches the app is already authenticated. Read identity from
injected headers:

- `X-User-Id` — unique user identifier
- `X-User-Email` — user email address
- `X-User-Verified` — `true` when email is verified

To allow unauthenticated access to a path, add it to `vibewarden.yaml`:

```yaml
auth:
  public_paths:
    - "/your/public/path"
```
{{ end }}
{{ if .RateLimitEnabled }}
## Rate limiting — DO NOT IMPLEMENT

Rate limiting is configured at {{ .RateLimitRPS }} req/s per IP in VibeWarden.
Do not add rate limiting middleware to the application.
{{ end }}
{{ if .TLSEnabled }}
## TLS — DO NOT CONFIGURE IN APP

TLS is terminated by VibeWarden. The app receives plain HTTP on port {{ .UpstreamPort }}.
{{ end }}
## Security headers — DO NOT SET IN APP

VibeWarden adds HSTS, X-Frame-Options, Content-Security-Policy, and other security
headers automatically. Do not set them in application code.

## Useful endpoints

- `GET /_vibewarden/health` — liveness probe (served by VibeWarden, not the app)
{{ if .AdminEnabled }}- `/_vibewarden/admin/*` — admin API, requires `X-Admin-Key` header{{ end }}

## Running the dev environment

Start everything with `./vibew dev`. This generates all runtime config
(Kratos, Docker Compose) into `.vibewarden/generated/` and starts the full stack.
Do not run `docker compose up` directly — use `./vibew dev` so that config is
generated from `vibewarden.yaml` first.

## Config

All config is in `vibewarden.yaml`. Edit it to change VibeWarden behaviour, then restart with `./vibew dev`.
Docs: https://vibewarden.dev/docs/config
